  <p class="page-desc">{ws.description}</p>

  <div class="worksheet-box">
    <div class="config-panel">
      <h3>Settings</h3>
      <div class="config-inputs">
        <div class="config-group">
          <label for="cfgPassages">Number of Passages</label>
          <input type="number" id="cfgPassages" value="5" min="3" max="8" />
        </div>
        <div class="config-group">
          <label for="cfgLevel">Difficulty Level</label>
          <select id="cfgLevel">
            <option value="easy">Easy</option>
            <option value="medium" selected>Medium</option>
            <option value="hard">Hard</option>
          </select>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="worksheet-actions">
      <button class="ws-btn primary" id="btnGenerate">Generate New</button>
      <button class="ws-btn print" id="btnPrint">Print</button>
      <label class="toggle-label">
        <input type="checkbox" id="toggleAnswers" />
        Show Answers
      </label>
    </div>

    <div class="worksheet-content" id="worksheetContent">
      <div class="worksheet-header-print">
        <h2>Main Idea Practice</h2>
        <div class="name-date">
          <span>Name: ___________________</span>
          <span>Date: ___________________</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-grid reading-grid" id="problemGrid"></div>
      <div class="answer-key hidden" id="answerKey">
        <h3>Answer Key</h3>
        <div class="answer-grid" id="answerGrid"></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <AdUnit slot="ws-mid" format="rectangle" />

  <article class="content-section">
    <h2>Why Main Idea Skills Matter</h2>
    <p>Identifying the main idea is one of the most essential reading comprehension skills students develop in elementary and middle school. The main idea is the central point or message of a passage, and being able to find it quickly helps students summarize texts, take better notes, answer test questions, and understand complex reading material across all subjects. Students who struggle with main idea identification often have difficulty with reading comprehension overall, making this skill a critical building block.</p>
    <p>These worksheets provide structured practice with short passages at three difficulty levels. Each passage is followed by a multiple-choice question asking students to identify the main idea. The wrong answer choices are designed to be plausible distractors, such as supporting details or ideas that are mentioned but are not the central point. This helps students learn to distinguish between what is important and what is merely interesting.</p>

    <h2>How to Find the Main Idea</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Read the entire passage first.</strong> Do not try to identify the main idea after reading just one sentence.</li>
      <li><strong>Ask yourself: What is this mostly about?</strong> The main idea should cover the whole passage, not just one part.</li>
      <li><strong>Look at the first and last sentences.</strong> Authors often state or restate the main idea in these positions.</li>
      <li><strong>Eliminate details.</strong> Supporting details explain or give examples of the main idea but are not the main idea themselves.</li>
      <li><strong>Watch for distractors.</strong> A detail mentioned in the passage may be true but too narrow to be the main idea.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Grade-Level Expectations</h2>
    <p>In grades 3-4, students are expected to identify the main idea of simple informational passages and name key supporting details. By grades 5-6, students should be able to determine the main idea of more complex texts and explain how it is supported by specific details, quotes, or examples. These worksheets scale accordingly: easy passages use straightforward language with a clearly stated main idea, while hard passages require inference and careful reading to determine the central message.</p>

    <h2>Related Worksheets</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="/worksheets/reading-cause-effect-worksheets/">Cause and Effect Worksheets</a> - Identify causes and effects in reading passages.</li>
      <li><a href="/worksheets/reading-inference-worksheets/">Making Inferences Worksheets</a> - Draw conclusions from text clues.</li>
      <li><a href="/worksheets/reading-sequencing-worksheets/">Sequencing Worksheets</a> - Put story events in the correct order.</li>
    </ul>
  </article>

  <AdUnit slot="ws-bottom" format="horizontal" />
</BaseLayout>

<script is:inline>
  var selected = [];

  var passageBank = {
    easy: [
      { text: "Dogs make wonderful pets for families. They are loyal and love to play with children. Dogs can be trained to follow commands and do tricks. Many families enjoy taking their dogs for walks in the park.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Dogs can do tricks", "B) Dogs make great family pets", "C) Families go to the park", "D) Children like to play"], answer: "B" },
      { text: "The sun gives us light and warmth every day. Plants need sunlight to grow. Without the sun, Earth would be very cold and dark. The sun is the most important star for life on our planet.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Plants need sunlight", "B) Earth would be dark without the sun", "C) The sun is essential for life on Earth", "D) The sun is a star"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "Recycling helps protect our planet. When we recycle paper, we save trees from being cut down. Recycling plastic keeps it out of the ocean. Everyone can help by putting recyclable items in the correct bins.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Paper comes from trees", "B) Plastic ends up in the ocean", "C) Recycling bins are important", "D) Recycling helps protect the environment"], answer: "D" },
      { text: "Butterflies go through four stages in their life. First, they start as tiny eggs. Then they become caterpillars and eat lots of leaves. Next, they form a chrysalis, and finally they emerge as beautiful butterflies.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Caterpillars eat leaves", "B) Butterflies are beautiful", "C) Butterflies go through four life stages", "D) Eggs are tiny"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "Drinking water is very important for your body. Water helps your brain think clearly. It keeps your skin healthy and helps you digest food. You should try to drink several glasses of water every day.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Water helps your brain", "B) You should drink glasses of water", "C) Drinking water is important for your health", "D) Water is good for your skin"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "Bees are very busy insects. They fly from flower to flower collecting nectar. Bees use the nectar to make honey. They also help flowers grow by spreading pollen from one plant to another.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Bees collect nectar", "B) Bees are hardworking and helpful insects", "C) Honey comes from nectar", "D) Pollen helps flowers grow"], answer: "B" },
      { text: "Libraries are great places to visit. You can borrow books for free and read about anything that interests you. Many libraries also have computers, movies, and fun programs for kids. A library card is all you need to get started.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Library cards are free", "B) Libraries have computers", "C) Libraries offer many free resources", "D) Kids enjoy library programs"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "Helmets protect your head when you ride a bike. A helmet absorbs the impact if you fall. Without a helmet, a fall could cause a serious head injury. Always wear a helmet that fits properly when cycling.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Falls can cause injuries", "B) Helmets should fit properly", "C) Wearing a helmet while biking keeps you safe", "D) Bike riding is dangerous"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "Penguins are birds that cannot fly. Instead, they are excellent swimmers. Their wings work like flippers to push them through the water. Penguins spend much of their time in the ocean catching fish to eat.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Penguins eat fish", "B) Penguins have wings", "C) Penguins are birds adapted for swimming, not flying", "D) Penguins live in the ocean"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "Breakfast is called the most important meal of the day. Eating a healthy breakfast gives you energy for school. It helps you concentrate and do better on tests. Try to eat fruits, grains, and protein each morning.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Tests are easier after breakfast", "B) Fruits are healthy", "C) Eating a healthy breakfast helps you perform well", "D) Breakfast has protein"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "Frogs begin life as tiny eggs laid in water. The eggs hatch into tadpoles that breathe through gills. Over time, tadpoles grow legs and lungs. Eventually, they become adult frogs that can live on land.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Tadpoles have gills", "B) Frogs lay eggs in water", "C) Frogs change a lot as they grow up", "D) Adult frogs live on land"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "Washing your hands helps stop germs from spreading. You should use soap and water for at least twenty seconds. Clean hands prevent colds, flu, and other illnesses. Always wash your hands before eating and after using the bathroom.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Use soap for twenty seconds", "B) Germs cause the flu", "C) Hand washing prevents the spread of germs and illness", "D) Wash hands before eating"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "The moon does not make its own light. It reflects light from the sun. The moon looks different each night because we see different amounts of the sunlit side. These changing shapes are called phases of the moon.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) The sun makes light", "B) The moon has phases because it reflects sunlight", "C) The moon changes shape", "D) We see different sides of the moon"], answer: "B" },
      { text: "Elephants are the largest land animals on Earth. They use their long trunks to drink water, grab food, and greet each other. Elephants live in family groups led by the oldest female. They are known for their excellent memory.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Elephants have trunks", "B) Elephants live in groups", "C) Elephants are large, social animals with unique features", "D) Female elephants lead the group"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "Clouds form when water vapor rises into the sky and cools down. The tiny water droplets stick together to make clouds. Different types of clouds bring different weather. Dark, thick clouds usually mean rain is coming.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Dark clouds mean rain", "B) Water vapor makes clouds", "C) Clouds form from water vapor and affect weather", "D) There are different types of clouds"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "Spiders spin webs to catch insects for food. The silk they produce is very strong for its size. Different spiders build different shapes of webs. Once an insect gets stuck, the spider wraps it up and saves it to eat.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Spider silk is strong", "B) Spiders use webs to catch their food", "C) Insects get stuck in webs", "D) Webs come in different shapes"], answer: "B" },
      { text: "Seeds need water, soil, and sunlight to grow into plants. First, the seed absorbs water and begins to sprout. Then roots grow down into the soil. Finally, a stem pushes up toward the light and leaves appear.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Roots grow into soil", "B) Seeds need water", "C) Seeds grow into plants when they have what they need", "D) Stems push toward light"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "Tornadoes are powerful spinning columns of air. They form during severe thunderstorms when warm and cold air meet. Tornadoes can destroy buildings and toss cars into the air. People should go to a basement or interior room during a tornado warning.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Tornadoes spin", "B) Thunderstorms are dangerous", "C) Tornadoes are powerful storms that can cause serious damage", "D) Basements are safe during tornadoes"], answer: "C" }
    ],
    medium: [
      { text: "Coral reefs are often called the rainforests of the sea because they support an incredible variety of marine life. Thousands of species of fish, sea turtles, and invertebrates depend on coral reefs for food and shelter. However, rising ocean temperatures and pollution are causing coral bleaching, which weakens and kills the coral. Scientists are working on ways to restore damaged reefs and protect these vital ecosystems.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Coral reefs are colorful", "B) Coral reefs are vital ecosystems that are threatened by environmental changes", "C) Scientists study coral", "D) Fish live in the ocean"], answer: "B" },
      { text: "Before the invention of the printing press in 1440, books were copied by hand, making them extremely expensive and rare. Johannes Gutenberg's movable type press allowed books to be produced quickly and cheaply for the first time. This revolutionary invention led to a dramatic increase in literacy across Europe. Ideas could now spread faster than ever before, fueling the Renaissance and the Scientific Revolution.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Gutenberg lived in the 1400s", "B) Books were once copied by hand", "C) The printing press transformed society by making books widely available", "D) The Renaissance happened in Europe"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "Monarch butterflies make one of the most remarkable migrations in the animal kingdom. Each fall, millions of monarchs fly up to 3,000 miles from Canada and the northern United States to central Mexico. They spend the winter clustered in fir trees before beginning the journey north in spring. Amazingly, no single butterfly completes the entire round trip; it takes multiple generations to finish the migration.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Butterflies cluster in fir trees", "B) Monarch butterflies undertake an extraordinary multi-generational migration", "C) Monarchs live in Canada", "D) The migration is 3,000 miles long"], answer: "B" },
      { text: "Getting enough sleep is crucial for students to do well in school. During sleep, the brain organizes and stores information learned during the day, a process essential for memory. Students who are sleep-deprived tend to have trouble paying attention, solving problems, and controlling their emotions. Experts recommend that children ages 6-12 get 9 to 12 hours of sleep each night.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) The brain stores information during sleep", "B) Children need 9 to 12 hours of sleep", "C) Adequate sleep is essential for students' academic performance and health", "D) Sleep-deprived students are emotional"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "The Great Wall of China stretches over 13,000 miles across northern China. Construction began more than 2,000 years ago to protect Chinese states from invasions. Hundreds of thousands of workers, including soldiers, peasants, and prisoners, built the wall over many centuries. Today, it is one of the most visited tourist attractions in the world and a symbol of Chinese history and engineering.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) The wall is 13,000 miles long", "B) Prisoners helped build the wall", "C) The Great Wall of China is a historic engineering achievement built for defense", "D) Tourists visit China"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "Honey never spoils. Archaeologists have found 3,000-year-old honey in Egyptian tombs that was still perfectly edible. Honey's long shelf life comes from its low moisture content, high acidity, and the natural hydrogen peroxide produced by bees. These properties make it nearly impossible for bacteria and microorganisms to grow in honey.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Egyptians stored honey in tombs", "B) Honey contains hydrogen peroxide", "C) Honey lasts indefinitely because of its unique chemical properties", "D) Bacteria cannot grow in acidic environments"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "Volunteering benefits both the community and the volunteer. People who volunteer regularly report feeling happier and more connected to their neighbors. Communities with active volunteers have cleaner parks, better-funded schools, and stronger support networks for those in need. Even a few hours a month can make a meaningful difference.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Volunteers clean parks", "B) Volunteering is beneficial for communities and the people who participate", "C) A few hours a month is enough", "D) Schools need funding"], answer: "B" },
      { text: "Octopuses are among the most intelligent invertebrates in the ocean. They can solve puzzles, open jars, and even use tools to protect themselves. Octopuses have three hearts and blue blood, and they can change color in a fraction of a second to camouflage themselves or communicate. Their remarkable abilities continue to fascinate scientists studying animal intelligence.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Octopuses have three hearts", "B) Octopuses can change color", "C) Octopuses are remarkably intelligent and have unique biological features", "D) Scientists study animal intelligence"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "Urban gardens are transforming empty city lots into productive green spaces. Residents grow vegetables, herbs, and flowers, providing fresh food in neighborhoods where grocery stores may be scarce. These gardens also reduce air pollution, manage stormwater runoff, and bring people together. Cities around the world are encouraging urban gardening through grants and community programs.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Empty lots are unused", "B) Urban gardens provide food, environmental, and social benefits to cities", "C) Herbs grow well in cities", "D) Cities offer grants for programs"], answer: "B" },
      { text: "The human body contains roughly 206 bones, but babies are born with about 270. As a child grows, many of these smaller bones fuse together to form larger, stronger bones. By the time a person reaches adulthood, the skeleton has settled into its final count of 206. Bones continue to rebuild and strengthen throughout life, especially with exercise and proper nutrition.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Babies have more bones than adults", "B) Exercise strengthens bones", "C) The human skeleton changes from birth to adulthood as bones fuse together", "D) Adults have 206 bones"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "Earthquakes occur when tectonic plates beneath Earth's surface suddenly shift. The energy released travels outward as seismic waves, shaking the ground and sometimes causing severe damage. Scientists use seismographs to measure the intensity of earthquakes on the Richter scale. While earthquakes cannot be predicted with certainty, building codes in earthquake-prone areas help reduce damage and save lives.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Tectonic plates cause earthquakes", "B) Seismographs measure earthquakes", "C) Earthquakes are caused by shifting plates and can be managed through preparation", "D) Building codes save lives"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "Wind turbines convert the kinetic energy of moving air into electricity. Modern wind farms can power thousands of homes without producing greenhouse gases. However, turbines can be expensive to install and may affect bird populations. Despite these challenges, wind energy is one of the fastest-growing sources of clean power worldwide.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Turbines are expensive", "B) Wind energy is a growing source of clean electricity with some challenges", "C) Birds are affected by turbines", "D) Wind farms power homes"], answer: "B" },
      { text: "Marie Curie was the first woman to win a Nobel Prize and remains the only person to win Nobel Prizes in two different sciences: physics and chemistry. Her research on radioactivity led to advances in medicine, including the development of X-ray machines used in hospitals. Despite facing discrimination as a woman in science, Curie's dedication and brilliance changed the world.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Curie won two Nobel Prizes", "B) X-ray machines are used in hospitals", "C) Marie Curie overcame barriers and made groundbreaking contributions to science", "D) Women faced discrimination in science"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "Composting turns food scraps and yard waste into nutrient-rich soil. Instead of sending banana peels, coffee grounds, and leaves to a landfill, you can pile them in a bin where microorganisms break them down naturally. The finished compost improves garden soil, reduces the need for chemical fertilizers, and keeps waste out of landfills.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Banana peels can be composted", "B) Composting converts waste into useful soil while reducing landfill burden", "C) Microorganisms break down waste", "D) Chemical fertilizers are harmful"], answer: "B" },
      { text: "Dolphins communicate using a complex system of clicks, whistles, and body movements. Each dolphin develops its own unique signature whistle that functions like a name. They use echolocation to find food and navigate murky waters. Researchers believe dolphin communication may be far more sophisticated than we currently understand.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Dolphins have signature whistles", "B) Echolocation helps dolphins find food", "C) Dolphins have a complex and possibly sophisticated communication system", "D) Researchers study dolphins"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "The Amazon rainforest produces about 20 percent of the world's oxygen, earning it the nickname 'the lungs of the Earth.' It is home to more species of plants and animals than any other place on the planet. Deforestation for farming and logging threatens this ecosystem. Protecting the Amazon is critical for biodiversity and the global climate.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) The Amazon produces oxygen", "B) Deforestation is caused by farming", "C) The Amazon rainforest is vital to the planet and must be protected", "D) Many species live in the Amazon"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "Eating a variety of colorful fruits and vegetables provides different vitamins and minerals your body needs. Red foods like tomatoes contain lycopene, which supports heart health. Orange foods like carrots are rich in vitamin A for good eyesight. Green vegetables provide iron and calcium. The more colors you eat, the more balanced your nutrition.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Tomatoes contain lycopene", "B) Carrots help your eyesight", "C) Eating colorful fruits and vegetables gives your body a range of essential nutrients", "D) Green vegetables have iron"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "Ancient Egyptians invented papyrus, one of the earliest forms of paper. They made it from the papyrus plant that grew along the Nile River. Strips of the plant were soaked, layered, and pressed together to create a smooth writing surface. Papyrus allowed Egyptians to keep records, write literature, and communicate across their vast empire.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Papyrus comes from a plant", "B) The Nile River was important to Egypt", "C) Ancient Egyptians created papyrus as an early writing material that advanced their civilization", "D) Egyptians wrote literature"], answer: "C" }
    ],
    hard: [
      { text: "Artificial intelligence is transforming healthcare by enabling faster and more accurate diagnoses. Machine learning algorithms can analyze medical images, such as X-rays and MRIs, to detect diseases like cancer at earlier stages than human doctors alone. AI also helps researchers identify potential drug candidates by simulating how molecules interact with biological targets. While AI shows enormous promise, experts emphasize that it should augment, not replace, the judgment and empathy of human physicians.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) AI can read X-rays", "B) AI is improving healthcare through better diagnostics and research while complementing human doctors", "C) Machine learning uses algorithms", "D) Doctors should be replaced by AI"], answer: "B" },
      { text: "The concept of zero took centuries to develop and was independently discovered by several ancient civilizations. The Babylonians used a placeholder symbol, the Mayans had a shell-shaped zero, and Indian mathematicians were the first to treat zero as a number in its own right. When the Indian concept of zero reached the Arab world and then Europe, it revolutionized mathematics by making positional number systems and advanced calculations possible.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) The Babylonians used a placeholder", "B) Zero was invented in India", "C) The development of zero across civilizations revolutionized mathematics", "D) Europeans learned about zero from Arabs"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "Microplastics, tiny fragments of plastic smaller than five millimeters, have been found in ocean water, drinking water, soil, and even the air we breathe. These particles come from the breakdown of larger plastic items, synthetic clothing fibers, and cosmetic products. Studies have detected microplastics in human blood, lungs, and placentas, raising concerns about potential health effects. Reducing single-use plastic and improving waste management are critical steps in addressing this growing environmental and health crisis.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Microplastics are smaller than five millimeters", "B) Synthetic clothing produces fibers", "C) Microplastics are a widespread environmental and health threat that requires urgent action", "D) Studies found plastics in blood"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "The placebo effect demonstrates the powerful connection between the mind and the body. In clinical trials, patients who receive a sugar pill or sham treatment sometimes experience real improvements in their symptoms simply because they believe they are receiving actual medicine. Brain scans show that placebos can trigger the release of endorphins and other chemicals that reduce pain and improve mood. Understanding the placebo effect is crucial for designing valid medical studies and exploring how belief influences physical health.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Sugar pills are used in clinical trials", "B) Endorphins reduce pain", "C) The placebo effect shows how belief can produce real physical changes and is important for medical research", "D) Brain scans detect chemical changes"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "Deep-sea hydrothermal vents support thriving ecosystems in complete darkness, thousands of meters below the ocean surface. Instead of relying on sunlight for energy like surface ecosystems, these communities are powered by chemosynthesis, a process in which bacteria convert chemicals from the vents into energy. Giant tube worms, clams, and shrimp cluster around the vents in densities that rival tropical rainforests. The discovery of these ecosystems challenged the long-held belief that all life on Earth ultimately depends on the sun.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Tube worms live near vents", "B) Chemosynthesis uses chemicals for energy", "C) Hydrothermal vent ecosystems thrive without sunlight, challenging assumptions about life on Earth", "D) The deep sea is very dark"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "The digital divide refers to the gap between people who have access to modern information technology and those who do not. In many rural and low-income communities, high-speed internet remains unavailable or unaffordable, limiting residents' ability to access education, healthcare, and job opportunities. The COVID-19 pandemic exposed the severity of this gap when millions of students could not attend online classes. Governments and organizations are investing in broadband infrastructure, but closing the divide requires sustained effort and equitable policy decisions.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Rural areas lack internet", "B) The digital divide creates inequality that requires deliberate effort and investment to close", "C) The pandemic moved school online", "D) Broadband infrastructure is expensive"], answer: "B" },
      { text: "Bioluminescence, the ability of living organisms to produce light, serves a variety of purposes in the natural world. Deep-sea fish use light to lure prey in pitch-black water. Fireflies flash to attract mates. Some species of squid release glowing ink to confuse predators. Scientists are studying bioluminescent proteins for medical applications, including tracking cancer cells and creating new diagnostic tools. Nature's light show is both beautiful and scientifically valuable.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Fireflies flash to attract mates", "B) Bioluminescence serves important natural functions and has promising scientific applications", "C) Deep-sea fish lure prey with light", "D) Scientists study squid ink"], answer: "B" },
      { text: "The concept of neuroplasticity has overturned the old belief that the adult brain is fixed and unchanging. Research now shows that the brain can form new neural connections throughout life in response to learning, experience, and even injury. Stroke patients can sometimes recover lost abilities as healthy parts of the brain take over functions of damaged areas. Musicians, athletes, and language learners all show measurable changes in brain structure related to their training. Neuroplasticity means that personal growth and cognitive improvement are possible at any age.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Stroke patients can recover", "B) Musicians have different brain structures", "C) Neuroplasticity shows the brain can change and grow throughout life, enabling ongoing development", "D) The old belief about brains was wrong"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "Space debris, consisting of defunct satellites, spent rocket stages, and collision fragments, poses a growing threat to active spacecraft and astronauts in orbit. There are currently over 27,000 pieces of debris large enough to be tracked, and millions more too small to detect. Even a paint flake traveling at orbital speeds can damage a spacecraft's window. Space agencies are developing technologies to remove debris, including robotic arms, nets, and lasers, but the problem worsens each year as more satellites are launched.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Paint flakes can damage spacecraft", "B) Space debris is an increasing hazard that requires new removal technologies", "C) There are 27,000 pieces of debris", "D) Robotic arms can catch debris"], answer: "B" },
      { text: "Indigenous peoples around the world have developed sophisticated systems of ecological knowledge over thousands of years. This traditional knowledge includes understanding of plant medicine, sustainable farming techniques, and wildlife behavior that Western science is only beginning to appreciate. Integrating indigenous knowledge with modern research has led to breakthroughs in conservation, agriculture, and pharmacology. Respecting and preserving this knowledge is both a matter of cultural heritage and a practical strategy for addressing environmental challenges.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Indigenous peoples know about plant medicine", "B) Western science is new compared to traditional knowledge", "C) Indigenous ecological knowledge is valuable for both cultural preservation and modern scientific progress", "D) Conservation has benefited from research"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "Quantum computing represents a fundamentally different approach to processing information compared to classical computers. While traditional computers use bits that are either 0 or 1, quantum computers use qubits that can exist in multiple states simultaneously through a property called superposition. This allows quantum computers to solve certain problems exponentially faster than classical machines. Applications include drug discovery, cryptography, and climate modeling, though practical, large-scale quantum computers are still years away from widespread use.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Qubits can be 0 and 1 at the same time", "B) Quantum computing is a new approach with transformative potential, though still in development", "C) Classical computers use bits", "D) Drug discovery benefits from quantum computing"], answer: "B" },
      { text: "The global decline in insect populations has alarmed ecologists because insects play irreplaceable roles in ecosystems. They pollinate roughly 75 percent of food crops, decompose organic waste, and form the base of many food chains. Habitat loss, pesticide use, light pollution, and climate change are driving the decline. Some studies estimate insect biomass has decreased by over 40 percent in recent decades. Without urgent action to reverse these trends, food systems and ecosystems face serious disruption.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Insects pollinate food crops", "B) Pesticides kill insects", "C) The declining insect population threatens ecosystems and food systems worldwide", "D) Insect biomass has dropped 40 percent"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "The fashion industry is one of the largest polluters in the world, responsible for about 10 percent of global carbon emissions and significant water pollution. Fast fashion encourages consumers to buy cheap, trendy clothing that is worn only a few times before being discarded. The rise of sustainable fashion seeks to combat this by promoting ethical sourcing, durable design, and recycling programs. Consumers who choose quality over quantity and support transparent brands can help drive meaningful change.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Fast fashion is cheap and trendy", "B) The fashion industry pollutes significantly, and sustainable practices offer a path to improvement", "C) Carbon emissions are a global problem", "D) Consumers should buy quality clothing"], answer: "B" },
      { text: "Sleep deprivation has effects that extend far beyond feeling tired. Chronic lack of sleep weakens the immune system, increases the risk of heart disease and diabetes, and impairs memory consolidation. Studies show that driving while sleep-deprived can be as dangerous as driving under the influence of alcohol. Despite these well-documented risks, many adults routinely get fewer than the recommended seven to nine hours of sleep, often due to work demands, screen time, and stress.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Tired driving is like drunk driving", "B) Adults need seven to nine hours of sleep", "C) Chronic sleep deprivation poses serious health and safety risks that many people underestimate", "D) Screen time interferes with sleep"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "Language endangerment is accelerating worldwide, with linguists estimating that nearly half of the roughly 7,000 languages currently spoken could disappear by the end of this century. When a language dies, the cultural knowledge, oral histories, and unique ways of understanding the world that it carries are lost forever. Efforts to preserve endangered languages include documentation projects, immersion schools, and digital archives. These initiatives require community involvement and sustained funding to succeed.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) There are 7,000 languages in the world", "B) Immersion schools teach endangered languages", "C) The rapid loss of languages threatens irreplaceable cultural knowledge and requires active preservation", "D) Linguists study languages"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "Vertical farming, the practice of growing crops in stacked layers inside controlled environments, is gaining attention as a potential solution to food security challenges. These indoor farms use LED lights, hydroponics, and climate control to grow produce year-round regardless of weather or season. They use up to 95 percent less water than traditional farms and eliminate the need for pesticides. However, the high energy costs of lighting and temperature regulation remain a significant barrier to widespread adoption.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) Vertical farms use LED lights", "B) Vertical farming offers food security benefits but faces energy cost challenges", "C) Hydroponics grows plants without soil", "D) Traditional farms use more water"], answer: "B" },
      { text: "The gut microbiome, the community of trillions of microorganisms living in the human digestive system, influences far more than digestion. Research has linked gut bacteria to immune function, mental health, weight regulation, and even brain development. An imbalanced microbiome has been associated with conditions ranging from allergies to depression. Maintaining a diverse microbiome through a varied diet rich in fiber, fermented foods, and whole grains appears to support overall health.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) The gut contains trillions of microorganisms", "B) Fermented foods support gut health", "C) The gut microbiome has wide-ranging effects on health beyond digestion", "D) An imbalanced microbiome causes allergies"], answer: "C" },
      { text: "Citizen science projects allow ordinary people to contribute to real scientific research by collecting data, classifying images, or reporting observations. Programs like eBird and Galaxy Zoo have produced datasets large enough to lead to peer-reviewed publications. Participants gain scientific literacy and a deeper connection to the natural world. For researchers, citizen science provides a way to gather data at scales impossible for any single laboratory, making it a powerful tool for fields ranging from ecology to astronomy.", question: "What is the main idea of this passage?", choices: ["A) eBird tracks bird sightings", "B) Citizen science benefits both researchers and participants by enabling large-scale data collection", "C) Galaxy Zoo classifies images", "D) Participants learn about science"], answer: "B" }
    ]
  };

  function shuffle(arr) {
    for (var i = arr.length - 1; i > 0; i--) {
      var j = Math.floor(Math.random() * (i + 1));
      var temp = arr[i]; arr[i] = arr[j]; arr[j] = temp;
    }
    return arr;
  }

  function generateProblems() {
    var count = parseInt(document.getElementById('cfgPassages').value, 10);
    var level = document.getElementById('cfgLevel').value;

    if (isNaN(count) || count < 3) count = 3;
    if (count > 8) count = 8;

    var pool = passageBank[level].slice();
    shuffle(pool);
    selected = pool.slice(0, Math.min(count, pool.length));

    renderProblems();
    renderAnswerKey();
    updateAnswerVisibility();
  }

  function renderProblems() {
    var grid = document.getElementById('problemGrid');
    var showAnswers = document.getElementById('toggleAnswers').checked;
    var html = '';

    for (var i = 0; i < selected.length; i++) {
      var p = selected[i];
      html += '<div class="reading-passage">';
      html += '<div class="problem-number">' + (i + 1) + ')</div>';
      html += '<div class="passage-text">' + p.text + '</div>';
      html += '<div class="passage-question"><strong>' + p.question + '</strong></div>';
      html += '<div class="passage-choices">';
      for (var j = 0; j < p.choices.length; j++) {
        var isCorrect = showAnswers && p.choices[j].charAt(0) === p.answer;
        html += '<div class="choice' + (isCorrect ? ' correct' : '') + '">' + p.choices[j] + '</div>';
      }
      html += '</div>';
      html += '</div>';
    }

    grid.innerHTML = html;
  }

  function renderAnswerKey() {
    var answerGrid = document.getElementById('answerGrid');
    var html = '';
    for (var i = 0; i < selected.length; i++) {
      html += '<div class="answer-item">';
      html += '<span class="q">' + (i + 1) + '.</span>';
      html += '<span class="a">' + selected[i].answer + '</span>';
      html += '</div>';
    }
    answerGrid.innerHTML = html;
  }

  function updateAnswerVisibility() {
    var showAnswers = document.getElementById('toggleAnswers').checked;
    var answerKey = document.getElementById('answerKey');
    if (showAnswers) { answerKey.classList.remove('hidden'); }
    else { answerKey.classList.add('hidden'); }
    renderProblems();
  }

  document.getElementById('btnGenerate').addEventListener('click', generateProblems);
  document.getElementById('btnPrint').addEventListener('click', function () { window.print(); });
  document.getElementById('toggleAnswers').addEventListener('change', updateAnswerVisibility);
  generateProblems();
</script>
